{"title_page": "Garuda Indonesia Flight 206", "text_new": "{{short description|Aircraft hijacking}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name            = Garuda Indonesia Flight 206\n|occurrence_type = Hijacking\n|image           = McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32, Garuda Indonesia JP5953083.jpg\n|caption         = A Garuda Indonesia McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32 similar to the aircraft involved\n|date            = 28 March 1981\n|type            = [[Aircraft hijacking|Hijacking]]\n|site            = [[Don Mueang International Airport|Don Mueang Airport]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n|aircraft_type   = [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]\n|aircraft_name   = \"Woyla\" \n|operator        = [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n|tail_number     = PK-GNJ\n|origin          = [[Kemayoran Airport]], [[Jakarta]]\n|stopover        = Talang Betutu Airport, [[Palembang]]\n|destination     = [[Soewondo Air Force Base|Polonia Airport]], [[Medan]]\n|passengers      = 48\n|crew            = 5\n|injuries        = 2\n|fatalities      = 5 (3 hijackers, 1 commando, and the pilot)\n|survivors       = 46\n}}\n\n'''Garuda Indonesia Flight 206''' was a [[Garuda Indonesia]] flight that was [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked]] on 28 March 1981, by the [[Komando Jihad]] in [[Indonesia]]. The [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]] plane PK-GNJ was hijacked on a [[domestic flight]] and forced to land at [[Don Mueang International Airport]] in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. The hijackers demanded the release of their confederates from Indonesian jails and issued other demands. Three days later, the aircraft was stormed by [[Kopassus|Indonesian special forces]]. In the ensuing gunfire, the pilot, one of the Kopassus operative and and three hijackers were killed, while all passengers were rescued.\n\n==Incident==\nThe McDonnell Douglas DC-9, named \"Woyla\", was scheduled to take off from [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II Airport]] in [[Palembang]], [[South Sumatra]], on Saturday morning, 28 March 1981. The pilot was Captain Herman Rante. The plane departed [[Kemayoran Airport]] in [[Jakarta]] at 08:00 and was scheduled to arrive at [[Polonia International Airport]] in [[Medan]], [[North Sumatra]], at 10:55. After take-off, five men with [[revolvers]] stood up from their seats. Some pointed their guns at the pilot, while others patrolled the aisle, monitoring passengers. They demanded the pilot fly to [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]], but the plane did not have enough fuel, so they refueled at [[Penang International Airport]] in [[Bayan Lepas]], [[Malaysia]]. When they were refueling, the hijackers removed an old lady named Hulda Panjaitan from the plane because she kept crying. Subsequently, the plane took off and landed at Don Mueang Airport in Bangkok. Once there, the hijackers read out their demands. The primary demand was the release of 80 individuals recently imprisoned in Indonesia following the \"Cicendo Event\" two weeks earlier, where Islamists attacked a police station in the Cicendo sub-district of [[Bandung]]. The hijackers also demanded US$1.5 million, that [[Adam Malik]] be suspended from the post of [[Vice President of Indonesia]], and that every [[Israelis|Israeli]] be deported from Indonesia. They also specified the release of one of their comrades at a secret location. The hijackers told Thai police to deliver their demands to the Indonesian government, and threatened to blow up the plane with all the passengers and crew aboard if their demands were not met.\n\nThe Deputy Commander of the Armed Forces, Admiral Sudomo, immediately ordered the [[Indonesian Army]]'s [[Kopassus]], to conduct a [[counter-terrorist]] raid to rescue the hostages. The commandos borrowed a McDonnell Douglas from Garuda Indonesia that was similar to the hijacked plane for three days to rehearse a [[Raid (military)|raid]]. The team was armed with new weapons, including [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]s. They set off for Thailand using a Garuda Indonesia [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]]. On Monday, 31 March 1981, the team was ready, but the [[Thai government]] did not give permission for Indonesian forces to take over the aircraft as it was on Thai territory. In desperation, the Indonesian Strategic Intelligence Chief [[Benny Moerdani]] contacted a friend at the [[CIA]] station in Bangkok to persuade the Thai government to give permission.\n\nThe Thai government finally approved the raid with the assistance of the [[Royal Thai Air Force Security Force Regiment]] (SFR). On Tuesday, 31 March, the team began the [[Hostage Rescue|hostage-rescue operation]], dividing themselves into three groups: Red Team, Blue Team, and Green Team. The Red and Blue teams were to be at the plane's rear while the Green team was to enter from the back door of the plane. Members of the Thai SFR team were positioned on the [[Airport apron|tarmac]] in the event hijackers tried to escape. When the Kopassus team entered the plane, the hijackers were surprised and fired at the team, but three of the hijackers were killed when the team returned fire. One of the Kopassus commandos was shot, probably by his comrades, as was the pilot. The hostages were released unharmed. Two of the hijackers surrendered to Thai commandos, but they were killed by the Kopassus commandos on the plane taking them back to Jakarta.<ref name=Conboy>{{cite book |author=Ken Conboy |title=Kopassus: Inside Indonesia's Special Forces |year=2004 |publisher=Equinox Publishing |isbn=979-95898-8-6 |pages=277\u2013278}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath== \nAchmad Kirang, the wounded Kopassus team member who was shot in the [[abdomen]], died the following day on 1 April 1981 at [[Bhumibol Adulyadej Hospital]] in Bangkok. Captain Herman Rante, the plane's pilot who was shot in the [[crossfire]], also died in Bangkok a few days later. Kirang and Rante's remains were transported from Bangkok to Jakarta, where they were both later interred in [[Kalibata Heroes Cemetery]].\n\nThe entire Kopassus team, including leader Lieutenant Colonel Sintong Panjaitan, were awarded the Bintang Sakti by the Indonesian government and were [[promoted]]. Achmad Kirang was [[wikt:Special:Search/posthumous|posthumously]] double promoted.<ref name=Wiwoho>{{cite book |author=B Wiwoho|title=Operasi Woyla - Pembebasan Pembajakan Pesawat Garuda Indonesia |year=2016 |publisher=Kompas Gramedia Group|page=151|isbn=978-602-412-122-8}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Air France Flight 8969]]\n* [[Singapore Airlines Flight 117]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Hutabarat, Arifin |title=To Our Beloved Country: The History of Garuda Indonesia |year=1989 |publisher=Ganesia P.R. |oclc=21396891 |page=54}}\n*{{cite book |author=Sebastian, Leonard C. |title=Realpolitik ideology: Indonesia's use of military force |year=2006 |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |isbn=981-230-310-3|page=168}}\n*{{cite book|author= Oktorino, N|title=Konflik Bersejarah-Greatest Raids|year=2013|publisher=Elex Media Computindo|isbn=9786020214498}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.komchadluek.net/detail/20120118/120574/%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%A2...%E0%B8%81%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%84%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A2.html#.UYFlwLUqz4Y Komchad Luek Newspaper, International terrorism that has occurred in Thailand. (Thai version)]\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1981}}\n{{Garuda Indonesia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Indonesia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Thailand}}\n\n[[Category:1981 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:1981 in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Aircraft hijackings]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1981]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Garuda Indonesia accidents and incidents|Flight 206]]\n[[Category:Hostage taking]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1981]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Asia in 1981]]\n[[Category:March 1981 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Indonesia in the 1980s]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aircraft hijacking}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name            = Garuda Indonesia Flight 206\n|occurrence_type = Hijacking\n|image           = McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32, Garuda Indonesia JP5953083.jpg\n|caption         = A Garuda Indonesia McDonnell Douglas DC-9-32 similar to the aircraft involved\n|date            = 28 March 1981\n|type            = [[Aircraft hijacking|Hijacking]]\n|site            = [[Don Mueang International Airport|Don Mueang Airport]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n|aircraft_type   = [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]]\n|aircraft_name   = \"Woyla\" \n|operator        = [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n|tail_number     = PK-GNJ\n|origin          = [[Kemayoran Airport]], [[Jakarta]]\n|stopover        = Talang Betutu Airport, [[Palembang]]\n|destination     = [[Soewondo Air Force Base|Polonia Airport]], [[Medan]]\n|passengers      = 48\n|crew            = 5\n|injuries        = 2\n|fatalities      = 5 (3 hijackers, 1 commando, and the pilot)\n|survivors       = 46\n}}\n\n'''Garuda Indonesia Flight 206''' was a [[Garuda Indonesia]] flight that was [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked]] on 28 March 1981, by the [[Komando Jihad]] in [[Indonesia]]. The [[McDonnell Douglas DC-9]] plane PK-GNJ was hijacked on a [[domestic flight]] and forced to land at [[Don Mueang International Airport]] in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. The hijackers demanded the release of their confederates from Indonesian jails and issued other demands. Three days later, the aircraft was stormed by [[Kopassus|Indonesian special forces]], who freed most of the passengers, and killed three hijackers, the pilot, and one of their colleagues.\n\n==Incident==\nThe McDonnell Douglas DC-9, named \"Woyla\", was scheduled to take off from [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II Airport]] in [[Palembang]], [[South Sumatra]], on Saturday morning, 28 March 1981. The pilot was Captain Herman Rante. The plane departed [[Kemayoran Airport]] in [[Jakarta]] at 08:00 and was scheduled to arrive at [[Polonia International Airport]] in [[Medan]], [[North Sumatra]], at 10:55. After take-off, five men with [[revolvers]] stood up from their seats. Some pointed their guns at the pilot, while others patrolled the aisle, monitoring passengers. They demanded the pilot fly to [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]], but the plane did not have enough fuel, so they refueled at [[Penang International Airport]] in [[Bayan Lepas]], [[Malaysia]]. When they were refueling, the hijackers removed an old lady named Hulda Panjaitan from the plane because she kept crying. Subsequently, the plane took off and landed at Don Mueang Airport in Bangkok. Once there, the hijackers read out their demands. The primary demand was the release of 80 individuals recently imprisoned in Indonesia following the \"Cicendo Event\" two weeks earlier, where Islamists attacked a police station in the Cicendo sub-district of [[Bandung]]. The hijackers also demanded US$1.5 million, that [[Adam Malik]] be suspended from the post of [[Vice President of Indonesia]], and that every [[Israelis|Israeli]] be deported from Indonesia. They also specified the release of one of their comrades at a secret location. The hijackers told Thai police to deliver their demands to the Indonesian government, and threatened to blow up the plane with all the passengers and crew aboard if their demands were not met.\n\nThe Deputy Commander of the Armed Forces, Admiral Sudomo, immediately ordered the [[Indonesian Army]]'s [[Kopassus]], to conduct a [[counter-terrorist]] raid to rescue the hostages. The commandos borrowed a McDonnell Douglas from Garuda Indonesia that was similar to the hijacked plane for three days to rehearse a [[Raid (military)|raid]]. The team was armed with new weapons, including [[Heckler & Koch MP5]]s. They set off for Thailand using a Garuda Indonesia [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]]. On Monday, 31 March 1981, the team was ready, but the [[Thai government]] did not give permission for Indonesian forces to take over the aircraft as it was on Thai territory. In desperation, the Indonesian Strategic Intelligence Chief [[Benny Moerdani]] contacted a friend at the [[CIA]] station in Bangkok to persuade the Thai government to give permission.\n\nThe Thai government finally approved the raid with the assistance of the [[Royal Thai Air Force Security Force Regiment]] (SFR). On Tuesday, 31 March, the team began the [[Hostage Rescue|hostage-rescue operation]], dividing themselves into three groups: Red Team, Blue Team, and Green Team. The Red and Blue teams were to be at the plane's rear while the Green team was to enter from the back door of the plane. Members of the Thai SFR team were positioned on the [[Airport apron|tarmac]] in the event hijackers tried to escape. When the Kopassus team entered the plane, the hijackers were surprised and fired at the team, but three of the hijackers were killed when the team returned fire. One of the Kopassus commandos was shot, probably by his comrades, as was the pilot. The hostages were released unharmed. Two of the hijackers surrendered to Thai commandos, but they were killed by the Kopassus commandos on the plane taking them back to Jakarta.<ref name=Conboy>{{cite book |author=Ken Conboy |title=Kopassus: Inside Indonesia's Special Forces |year=2004 |publisher=Equinox Publishing |isbn=979-95898-8-6 |pages=277\u2013278}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath== \nAchmad Kirang, the wounded Kopassus team member who was shot in the [[abdomen]], died the following day on 1 April 1981 at [[Bhumibol Adulyadej Hospital]] in Bangkok. Captain Herman Rante, the plane's pilot who was shot in the [[crossfire]], also died in Bangkok a few days later. Kirang and Rante's remains were transported from Bangkok to Jakarta, where they were both later interred in [[Kalibata Heroes Cemetery]].\n\nThe entire Kopassus team, including leader Lieutenant Colonel Sintong Panjaitan, were awarded the Bintang Sakti by the Indonesian government and were [[promoted]]. Achmad Kirang was [[wikt:Special:Search/posthumous|posthumously]] double promoted.<ref name=Wiwoho>{{cite book |author=B Wiwoho|title=Operasi Woyla - Pembebasan Pembajakan Pesawat Garuda Indonesia |year=2016 |publisher=Kompas Gramedia Group|page=151|isbn=978-602-412-122-8}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Air France Flight 8969]]\n* [[Singapore Airlines Flight 117]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Hutabarat, Arifin |title=To Our Beloved Country: The History of Garuda Indonesia |year=1989 |publisher=Ganesia P.R. |oclc=21396891 |page=54}}\n*{{cite book |author=Sebastian, Leonard C. |title=Realpolitik ideology: Indonesia's use of military force |year=2006 |publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |isbn=981-230-310-3|page=168}}\n*{{cite book|author= Oktorino, N|title=Konflik Bersejarah-Greatest Raids|year=2013|publisher=Elex Media Computindo|isbn=9786020214498}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.komchadluek.net/detail/20120118/120574/%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%A2...%E0%B8%81%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%84%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%A2.html#.UYFlwLUqz4Y Komchad Luek Newspaper, International terrorism that has occurred in Thailand. (Thai version)]\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1981}}\n{{Garuda Indonesia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Indonesia}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Thailand}}\n\n[[Category:1981 in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:1981 in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Aircraft hijackings]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1981]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Garuda Indonesia accidents and incidents|Flight 206]]\n[[Category:Hostage taking]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1981]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Asia in 1981]]\n[[Category:March 1981 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Indonesia in the 1980s]]\n", "name_user": "Cal1407", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garuda_Indonesia_Flight_206"}
{"title_page": "Kalwan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name  = Kalwan\n| native_name = \u0915\u0933\u0935\u0923\n| native_name_lang   = Marathi ( ihyrani )\n| other_name  = \n| nickname = \n| settlement_type = tehsil\n| image_skyline  = \n| image_alt  = \n| image_caption     = \n| pushpin_map  = India Maharashtra\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Maharashtra, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|20|29|25|N|74|01|35|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = Nashik\n| established_title = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 859.71\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 346000\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = Kalwankar\n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Language\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1  = [[Marathi language|Marathi,Kokani,Ahirani,English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 423501\n| registration_plate      = MH 41\n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1  = [[Satana (India)|Satana]] [[Nashik]]\n| website  = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Kalwan''' is a [[tahsil|tehsil]] in Kalwan subdivision of [[Nashik District]] in [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. Kalwan is situated 80&nbsp;km from [[Nashik]] and 251&nbsp;km from state capital [[Mumbai]].  [[Saptashrungi]] Gad, a religious shrine of Goddess Saptashrungi, is situated in Kalwan taluka. Saptashrungi Gad is located 22&nbsp;km from Kalwan city. [[Dhodap]] hill fort, which is a popular mountain climbing destination and 3rd highest peak in [[Maharashtra]], is situated 8&nbsp;km from Kalwan city. [[Abhona]] is the largest town in Kalwan tehsil after Kalwan city.<ref>[http://nashik.nic.in/htmldocs/taluka_kalvan.htm \"Block Profile of Kalvan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410074141/http://nashik.nic.in/htmldocs/taluka_kalvan.htm |date=10 April 2009 }} Official WebSite of Nashik District</ref> Kalwan is situated in the delta of Behadi and Girana river. Black soil and ample water are available  for cultivation of cash crops. This significantly contributes to the GDP of Kalwan tehsil.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Talukas in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Nashik district]]\n\n\n{{Nashik-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name  = Kalwan\n| native_name = \u0915\u0933\u0935\u0923\n| native_name_lang   = Marathi ( ihyrani )\n| other_name  = \n| nickname = \n| settlement_type = tehsil\n| image_skyline  = \n| image_alt  = \n| image_caption     = \n| pushpin_map  = India Maharashtra\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Maharashtra, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|20|29|25|N|74|01|35|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = Nashik\n| established_title = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 859.71\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 346000\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = Kalwankar\n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Language\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1  = [[Marathi language|Marathi,Kokani,Ahirani,English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 423501\n| registration_plate      = MH 41\n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1  = [[Satana (India)|Satana]] [[Nashik]]\n| website  = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Kalwan''' is a [[tahsil|thsil]] in Kalwan subdivision of [[Nashik District]] in [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. Kalwan is situated 80&nbsp;km from [[Nashik]] and 251&nbsp;km from state capital [[Mumbai]].  [[Saptashrungi]] Gad, a religious shrine of Goddess Saptashrungi, is situated in Kalwan taluka. Saptashrungi Gad is located 22&nbsp;km from Kalwan city. [[Dhodap]] hill fort, which is a popular mountain climbing destination and 3rd highest peak in [[Maharashtra]], is situated 8&nbsp;km from Kalwan city. [[Abhona]] is the largest town in Kalwan tehsil after Kalwan city.<ref>[http://nashik.nic.in/htmldocs/taluka_kalvan.htm \"Block Profile of Kalvan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410074141/http://nashik.nic.in/htmldocs/taluka_kalvan.htm |date=10 April 2009 }} Official WebSite of Nashik District</ref> Kalwan is situated in the delta of Behadi and Girana river. Black soil and ample water are available  for cultivation of cash crops. This significantly contributes to the GDP of Kalwan tehsil.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Talukas in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Nashik district]]\n\n\n{{Nashik-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ramesh.kambleadtbaramati", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalwan"}
{"title_page": "China\u2013South Korea relations", "text_new": "{{For|the relations between South Korea and the Taipei-based Republic of China, commonly known as Taiwan, South Korea\u2013Taiwan relations}}\n{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the People's Republic of China and South Korea}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|China\u2013South Korea|China|South Korea|envoytitle1 =[[Ambassadors of China|Ambassador]] |envoy1 = [[Qiu Guohong]]|envoytitle2 =[[Ambassadors of South Korea|Ambassador]] |envoy2 = [[Jang Ha-sung]]|mission1 = [[Embassy of People's Republic of China in South Korea|Chinese Embassy, Seoul]] |mission2 = [[Embassy of South Korea in China|Korean Embassy, Beijing]]}}\n[[File:Kr-china-embassy 201604.JPG|thumb|Chinese Embassy in [[Seoul]], South Korea.]]\n[[File:\u97e9\u56fd\u9a7b\u4e2d\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9986.jpg|thumb|right|South Korean Embassy in [[Beijing]], China.]]\n\n[[Diplomatic relations]] between the [[China|People's Republic of China]] (PRC) and the Republic of Korea ([[South Korea]]) were formally established in the 1980s. Before then, the PRC recognized only the Democratic People's Republic of Korea ([[North Korea]]) while South Korea in turn recognized only the [[Republic of China]] ([[Taiwan]]). South Korea was the last Asian country to establish relations with the People's Republic of China. In recent years, China and South Korea have endeavored to boost their strategic and cooperative partnership in numerous sectors, as well as promoting high level relationship.<ref>http://www.korea.net/news.do?mode=detail&guid=47084</ref> Trade, tourism and multiculturalism, specifically, have been the most important factors of strengthening two neighbouring countries cooperative partnership.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe relations significantly deteriorated after South Korea announced its intentions to deploy [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]], a move that China strongly opposed. China imposed an unofficial boycott on South Korea in an attempt to stop them from deploying the missile system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/2083166/opinion-why-chinas-shadow-boycott-south-korea-self-defeating|title=Why China's economic jabs at South Korea are self-defeating|date=2017-04-02|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> However, at the end of October 2017, the two countries ended the 1-year-long diplomatic dispute and have been working swiftly to get their relationship back on track since, strengthening exchanges and cooperation between each other, creating harmony of interests, and agreed to resume exchanges and cooperation in all areas. All economic and cultural bans from China towards South Korea were also lifted as a result, with political and security cooperation, businesses and cultural exchanges between the two countries getting back to healthy state.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea, China say to mend ties after THAAD standoff|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/south-korea--china-say-to-mend-ties-after-thaad-standoff-9360436?view=DEFAULT|work=Channel NewsAsia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=China, South Korea agree to mend ties after THAAD standoff|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles/china-south-korea-agree-to-mend-ties-after-thaad-standoff-idUSKBN1D003G|work=Reuters|date=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=CNN|first1=Ben Westcott and Lauren Suk|title=China, South Korea end year-long diplomatic feud over missile system|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/31/asia/china-south-korea-thaad/index.html|work=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=AP|first1=Hyung-Jin Kim /|title=China, South Korea Ease Tensions Over U.S. Missile Defense|url=http://time.com/5003532/south-korea-china-thaad-missile-defense/|work=Time}}</ref>\n\nUpon resumption of relationship, China and South Korea have been organizing presidential and governmental visits, working together on the [[Korean Peninsula]], assisting with the development of other countries, and cooperating in numerous areas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jennings|first1=Ralph|title=South Korea Vying with China as New Benefactor for Philippines|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/south-korea-competing-with-china-in-philippine-trade/4126200.html|work=VOA|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diplomat|first1=Charlotte Gao, The|title=South Korean Foreign Minister to Visit Beijing After China Envoy's North Korea Visit|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/11/south-korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-beijing-after-china-envoys-north-korea-visit/|work=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=South Korean foreign minister to visit China to arrange presidential trip- Nikkei Asian Review|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/South-Korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-China-to-arrange-presidential-trip|work=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en|access-date=2017-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121065955/https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/South-Korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-China-to-arrange-presidential-trip|archive-date=2017-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Seoul to closely cooperate with China, Japan to tackle North Korea issue|url=https://www.upi.com/Seoul-to-closely-cooperate-with-China-Japan-to-tackle-North-Korea-issue/8351520929245/|work=UPI|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History of relations==\n{{See also|History of Sino-Korean relations|}}\n\n===Korean War===\n{{main|Korean War}}\nThe newly established [[People's Republic of China]] participated in the [[Korean War]] between 1950 and 1953, sending the [[People's Volunteer Army]] to fight alongside [[Soviet Union]] and against [[United States]] and [[United Nations]] troops in October 1950. It successfully drove the UN forces out of North Korea, but its own offensive into the South itself was repelled. The participation of the PVA strained relations between South Korea and China. The Korean War concluded in July 1953, resulting in the establishment of the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]], and the eventual withdrawal of Chinese forces from the Korean Peninsula. US troops though have remained in South Korea to this day.\n\n===Cold War===\nThroughout the [[Cold War]], there were no official relations between the PRC and ROK. The PRC maintained close relations with [[North Korea]], and South Korea maintained diplomatic relations with the Republic of China in [[Taiwan]]. This hindered trade between Seoul and Beijing, because South Korea was unable to protect its citizens and business interests in China without some form of international agreements. Beijing's economic needs involving South Korea were initially eclipsed by those of [[Moscow]].{{Clarify|reason=|date=May 2019}}<!-- what do you mean by \"eclipsed by those of Moscow\"? -->\n\n====Relations under Park and Chun (1961\u20131988)====\nPresident [[Park Chung-hee]] initiated and President [[Chun Doo-hwan]] advanced a policy of establishing relations with China and the [[Soviet Union]], and attempting to improve those with [[North Korea]]. China and the USSR had significant sway in determining the future of the [[Korean Peninsula]]. Good relations with old allies of North Korea were therefore integral to the [[Nordpolitik]] policy.\n\n[[Seoul]]'s official contact with Beijing started by the landing of a hijacked [[CAAC Flight 296]] in May 1983. China sent a delegation of thirty-three officials to Seoul to negotiate its return. This marked the beginning of a series of casual exchanges of citizens. For example, in March 1984, a South Korean tennis team visited [[Kunming]] for a [[1984 Davis Cup#Eastern Zone|Davis Cup]] match with a Chinese team. In April 1984, a thirty-four-member Chinese basketball team arrived in Seoul to participate in the Eighth Asian Junior Basketball Championships. Some Chinese officials reportedly paid quiet visits to South Korea to inspect its industries, while South Korean officials visited China to attend a range of international conferences.\n\n====Late 1980s====\nActive South Korean-Chinese individual contacts have been encouraged. Academics, journalists, and particularly families divided between South Korea and China were able to exchange visits freely in the late 1980s. Significant numbers of citizens of each country reside in the other. {{Asof|2009}}, more than 600,000 [[Chinese people in Korea|PRC citizens reside in South Korea]], of whom 70% are [[Koreans in China|ethnic Koreans]] from the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture]] in China's [[Jilin Province]] and other parts of China, while roughly 560,000 South Korean citizens lived in China.<ref name=\"BBG\">{{citation|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=ahEY6TmQOzIc&refer=home|periodical=Bloomberg L.P.|title=South Koreans Quit China as Yuan's Gain Raises Cost of Living|last=Kim|first=Kyoungwha|date=2009-01-09|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ChosunIlbo20090806\">{{citation|periodical=Chosun Ilbo|date=2009-08-06|accessdate=2009-10-18|title=More Than 1 Million Foreigners Live in Korea|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/08/06/2009080600243.html}}</ref>\n\nHowever, during this period significant barriers to strong trade and relations persisted. The absence of any protections granted by official relations had still remained. Beijing has been politically closer to Pyongyang, and relations with North Korea remained tense and distrustful.\n\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square protests]] Pyongyang publicly supported of Beijing's actions. Seoul, on the other hand, did not condone or condemn the actions in Tiananmen Square.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Post Cold War and Reform and Opening Up==\nTrade between the two countries continued to increase nonetheless, especially after the PRC's [[reform and opening up]]. Furthermore, China has attempted to mediate between North Korea and the US; between North Korea and Japan; and also initiated and promoted tripartite talks\u2014between Pyongyang, Seoul, and Washington.<ref>Zhao, Quansheng. \"China and the Korean Peace Process.\" In the Korean Peace Processand the Four Powers. Burlington: Ashgate, 2003.</ref>\n\nSouth Korea had been an ally of the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]]. But in 1992 diplomatic ties between Seoul and Taipei were nevertheless severed. On August 24, 1992 formal diplomatic relations were established between Seoul and Beijing. By 2004 China had become South Korea's leading trading partner.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Comrades in Broken Arms: Shifting Chinese Policies Toward North Korea Pg.580</ref>\n\nAfter the [[United States\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement|KORUS FTA]] (United States-Korea Free Trade Agreement) was finalized on 30 June 2007, the Chinese government immediately began seeking an FTA agreement with South Korea.<ref>\"ROK\u2019s Yonhap: Exports have been Remarkable, but can S. Korea Sustain Momentum?\" Yonhap, October 21, 2004, FBIS, KPP20041021000040.\n</ref> The [[China\u2013South Korea Free Trade Agreement|China-Republic of Korea Free Trade Agreement]] was finalized on December 20, 2015. Tariffs on 958 products including medical equipment, transformers, etc. were eliminated. On 1 January 2016, tariffs were eliminated on 5,779 products for 2 years. Also, in 10 years it is estimated that the Chinese tariffs will gradually go down and be eliminated on 5,846 products.<ref>\"China-Korea FTA.\" China FTA Network. Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China, n.d. Web.</ref> South Korea has been running a trade surplus with China, which hit a record US$32.5 billion in 2009 and total trade between the two nations surpassed US$300 billion in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.ce.cn/World/biz/201001/14/t20100114_20800769.shtml|title=S Korea posts record-high trade surplus in 2009|date=2010-01-14}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOn 29 November 2010, a [[United States diplomatic cables leak]] mentioned two unknown Chinese officials telling then Vice-Foreign Minister [[Chun Yung-woo]] that the PRC would favor a Korea reunified under the South's government, as long as it was not hostile to China.<ref>Tisdall, Simon. \"Wikileaks Cables Reveal China 'ready to Abandon North Korea'\" The Guardian, 29 Nov. 2010. Web. 7 Dec. 2010. <https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/29/wikileaks-cables-china-reunified-korea></ref>\n\n[[File:Belt and Road Initiative participant map.svg|thumb|Countries which signed cooperation documents related to the [[Belt and Road Initiative]]]]\nIt was announced on 10 January 2011 that the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (South Korea)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade (MOFAT)]] established two teams of China experts and language specialists under its department handling Chinese affairs in an effort to strengthen diplomacy.<ref>Moore, Thomas G. \"China's International Relations: The Economic Dimension.\" In The International Relations of Northeast Asia. Lanham, Md.: Rowman and Littlefield Publishers, Inc., 2004, 101.</ref> An analytical team will report on political, economic and foreign affairs developments in China, and a monitoring team consisting of seven language specialists will report on public sentiment in China. The Institute of Foreign Affairs and National Security (IFANS), a think-tank affiliated to MOFAT, also launched a centre dedicated to China affairs, which will act as a hub to collate research on China undertaken in Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.junotane.com/analytical-updates/korea-strengthens-china-analyst-team.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713125430/http://www.junotane.com/analytical-updates/korea-strengthens-china-analyst-team.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-13 |title=Korea strengthens China analyst team |date=2011-01-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe Park-Xi summit in 2013 showed promise of warming relations, but this quickly chilled after China extended their [[Air Defense Identification Zone (East China Sea)]] over South Korean territory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/is-the-china-south-korea-honeymoon-over/ |title=Is the China-South Korea Honeymoon Over? |last1=Miller |first1=J. Berkshire |date=30 November 2013 |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> Despite this, in July 2014, Xi visited South Korea before its traditional ally North Korea, and in their talks, both leaders affirmed their support for a nuclear-free Korean peninsula and the ongoing free trade agreement negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/04/world/asia/presidents-of-china-and-south-korea-reaffirm-push-for-north-korean-denuclearization.html |title = China and South Korea Affirm Antinuclear Goals|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2014-07-03|last1 = Perlez|first1 = Jane}}</ref> Both leaders also expressed their concerns over Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]]'s reinterpretation of [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution]].\n\nIn October 2016, South Korea lodged a formal complaint with Beijing accusing Chinese fishing boats of ramming and sinking a South Korean coast guard vessel. The incident occurred on 7 October when South Korean coast guard officers were trying to stop about 40 Chinese fishing boats from suspected [[illegal fishing]] off South Korea's west coast.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/seoul-protests-to-beijing-over-sinking-of-coast-guard-vessel/2016/10/10/4654fa68-8eb8-11e6-bc00-1a9756d4111b_story.html</ref> The incidents of illegal Chinese entry continued and in 1 November 2016, South Korea ships opened fire on illegal Chinese boats. No casualties were reported.<ref>http://www.businessinsider.com/south-korea-fired-on-chinese-fishing-boats-2016-11</ref>\n\n===Deployment of THAAD in South Korea===\n\n==== Background ====\n \n[[File:Chinese tourist to South Korea.svg|thumb|right|Chinese tourists to South Korea and year-on-year rate. From March 2017, tourists plummeted in retaliation for the installation of THAAD.]]\nIn late 2016, the United States and South Korea jointly announced the deployment of the [[Terminal High-Altitude Area Defense]] (THAAD), allegedly in response to nuclear and missile threats by North Korea.<ref>Sherman, Paul Haenle and Anne. \"The Real Answer to China's THAAD Dilemma.\" The Diplomat. The Diplomat, 12 Sept. 2016.</ref> The U.S. states that the deployment of the THAAD is \u201cpurely a defensive measure\u2026 only aimed at North Korea\u201d and has no intention to threaten China's security interests. But China has continuously expressed its opposition over South Korea and U.S.\u2019s decision because of its concern that the deployment of THAAD might be a measure by the U.S. to contain China.<ref>\"Background Briefing with a Senior Administration Official on National Security Advisor Susan Rice's Visit to China July 26, 2016.\" Beijing/China. Embassy of the United States, n.d. Web.</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Reuters]]:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-missiledefence-idUSKBN1JV35W|title='No Nukes, No THAAD': South Korean town calls for missile defense...|date=2018-07-06|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-28|language=en}}</ref><blockquote>\u201cIt was China, not North Korea, that was the most uncomfortable with the idea of deploying THAAD in South Korea,\u201d said Yang Uk, a military expert at the Korea Defense and Security Forum. Beijing opposed THAAD and its powerful radar that can see deeply into Chinese territory, saying it upsets the regional security balance.</blockquote>\n\n==== Opposition from China ====\n\nStating that the THAAD will undermine China's own nuclear deterrent capability, China\u2019s Ambassador [[Qiu Guohong]] warned that the deployment of THAAD could \u201cdestroy\u201d the China\u2013South Korea ties in an instant, whereas the spokesperson of the president of South Korea warned China that deploying the THAAD is a \u201cmatter we will decide upon according to our own security and national interests.\" <ref>Tiezzi, Shannon. \"China Warns THAAD Deployment Could Destroy South Korea Ties 'in an Instant'\" The Diplomat. The Diplomat, 25 Feb. 2016.</ref>\n\nFor aims of a [[d\u00e9tente]] (a relaxation of tension), China and South Korea held a summit in [[Hangzhou]], eastern China, on Sept. 5, 2016 with each party's leaders [[Xi Jinping]] and [[Park Geun-hye|Park Geun-Hye]] to discuss the issue of THAAD. During the summit, Park reemphasized that the THAAD deployment is only to be aimed against North Korea and that there should be no reason for China's security interest to be concerned. However, Xi reiterated China's firm stance against the deployment of THAAD stating that it could \u201cintensify disputes\". Yet, the two countries still emphasized the long history of their relationship and agreed that a stable and healthy bilateral relationship will benefit both countries.<ref>Song, Sang-Ho. \"Yonhap News Agency.\" (6th LD) Park, Xi Reconfirm Differences pt. 2016.</ref>\n\n==== Effect of THAAD on South Korea's economy ====\n[[File:Hyundai Motor Sales in China.svg|thumb|right|Unit sales and year-on-year rate in China. From March 2017, unit sales plummeted in retaliation for the installation of [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]].]]\nWith South Korea's decision in 2017 to accept the deployment of [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]] in the country, although China's government shied away from formal sanctions and measures, it has urged its citizens through official media to express their displeasure and ill will at South Korea over the move.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-china-blog-39254254</ref> Chinese citizens were allowed to gather to protest. The news media has reported of citizen boycotts of South Korean products like [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]] cars, of South Korean goods being removed from supermarket shelves, and tourists and travel companies canceling trips to South Korea.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\" />\n\nSouth Korean conglomerate [[Lotte (conglomerate)|Lotte Group]] became a particular focus. Lotte had agreed to an exchange of land, a golf course in [[Seongju County|Seongju]], with the South Korean government that will be used for the THAAD deployment. In addition to a consumer boycott of Lotte stores in China, municipal authorities suddenly discovered that Lotte stores and factories to be in contravention of [[fire safety]] regulations and other local ordinances which has resulted in the closure of 75 out of 99 Lotte supermarkets.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen|first1=Jethro|last2=Han |first2=Sol |date=7 March 2017|title=One company is bearing the brunt of China's anger over U.S. missile system |url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/03/07/news/china-lotte-thaad-south-korea-tensions/ | work=[[CNN Money]] |location= |access-date=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Javier |last2=Guo |first2=Owen |last3=McMorrow |first3=Ryan  |date=9 March 2017 \n|title=South Korean Stores Feel China's Wrath as U.S. Missile System Is Deployed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/world/asia/china-lotte-thaad-south-korea.html?_r=0 | work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |access-date=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nMarch sales of Hyundai and its sister brand [[Kia Motors]] in China plunged 52 per cent from a year earlier to 72,000 vehicles, the lowest level since 2014.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\">{{cite web |title=South Korea's Hyundai, Kia sales halve in China amid diplomatic spat over THAAD |date=5 April 2017 |publisher=South China Morning Post |url=http://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2085118/south-koreas-hyundai-kia-sales-halve-china-amid-diplomatic-spat}}</ref> Chinese tourism also plummeted 39.4% (compared to March 2016) in March.<ref>{{cite web |title=3\uc6d4 \uc911\uad6d\uc778 \uad00\uad11\uac1d 39% \uc904\uc5b4\u2026 '\uc0ac\ub4dc \ubcf4\ubcf5' \uc601\ud5a5 |trans-title=Chinese tourists decrease by 39% in March ... Impact of 'THAAD Revenge' |publisher=Yonhapnews |date=April 5, 2017 \n|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2017/04/05/0200000000AKR20170405120251030.HTML}}</ref> As a result, China has become a more hated country in South Korea than even Japan, according to an opinion poll conducted by the [[Asan Institute for Policy Studies]] in March 2017.<ref>Alex Linder(2017-03-22):[http://shanghaiist.com/2017/03/22/south_koreans_like_japan_over_china.php South Koreans now hate China even more than Japan, new opinion polls says], ''[[Shanghaiist]]''</ref>\n\nAs a result, South Korea's distribution industry suffered. Chinese consumers were no longer attracted to Korean products and Chinese retailers boycotted Korean products. As a result of decreased Chinese consumption, South Korean department stores, duty-free, restaurants, and the automobile industry were severely affected. However, Korean conglomerates had to survive since China is the largest market in the world.\n\nHyundai had to stop the operation of Chinese factories and the economic losses were significant. The vicious cycle has been repeated as the decline of sales volume caused production suspension. Chinese automobile component manufacturing companies suspended distribution to Hyundai automobile factories that are located in China and it negatively affected the management of Hyundai automobile. THAAD had a tremendous impact on Korean economy in various business sectors and tarnished the brand value of Korean companies because of political reasons.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==== Culture ====\nKorean culture, singers, actors and dancers are popular with Chinese youth because of the development of the internet and export of Korean cultural content. After the THAAD dispute took place, a \"Korea limitation order\" ({{zh|s=\u9650\u97e9\u4ee4}}) was placed upon [[Hallyu]]. In China, Hallyu cultural events were canceled, Korean actors had to quit from their works and limited Korean media could be exported to China. The ban was lifted soon after, and relations cooled.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Historical controversies==\nThe Chinese historical claims surrounding [[Goguryeo]] and its related kingdoms created some tension between Korea and the PRC.<ref>[http://www.ou.edu/uschina/gries/articles/texts/Gries2005KoguryoEAIQ.pdf 02Gries.pmd<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The PRC government has recently begun the [[Northeast Project]], a controversial Chinese government research project claiming [[Goguryeo]] and other various Korean kingdoms, including [[Gojoseon]], [[Buyeo kingdom|Buyeo]] and [[Balhae]], to be Chinese tributary states. This sparked a massive uproar in South Korea when the project was widely publicized in 2004.<ref name=\"news.naver.com\">Donga Monthly. http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=037&aid=0000006961</ref>\n\n== Joint stance on Japan ==\n{{Main|History of Sino-Japanese relations|People's Republic of China\u2013Japan relations|History of Japan\u2013Korea relations|Japan\u2013South Korea relations|Japan\u2013Korea disputes}}\nDue to the [[Empire of Japan]] and atrocities committed by the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] on both Koreans and Chinese, from women who supplied sex during WWII(known as [[comfort women]]) and the [[Japanese colonization of Korea]] to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] and [[Unit 731]], South Korea and China are unified in their stance against Japan and insistence on greater reparations for Japan wartime atrocities.\n\n=== 1910-1945 provisional ROK government ===\n{{Main|Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea}}\nWhen the Korean peninsula was colonized by Imperial Japan, [[Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea|the provisional government of the ROK]] in exile in Shanghai received the support of China.\n\n=== Japanese war crimes ===\nBoth the governments of China and South Korea take a firm stand on issues in relation to [[Japanese war crimes]]. Korea had been under [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]] after the collapse of the [[Joseon Dynasty]] in 1910. During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], [[Japan]] invaded and occupied eastern China.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] perpetrated many war crimes against both Chinese and Koreans. This has caused both to oppose the Japanese government's stand on war crimes committed during the war. Issues where both the Chinese and South Korean governments stand together include the controversial visits of Japanese politicians to the [[Yasukuni Shrine]], the [[Japanese history textbook controversies]], and [[comfort women]].\n\n=== An Jung-geun ===\nIn 2014, a memorial dedicated to Korean assassin [[An Jung-geun]] was opened in the Chinese city of [[Harbin]], where he assassinated Japanese Prime Minister [[It\u014d Hirobumi]] in 1909. The Japanese government protested the move, referring to An as a \"terrorist\".<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Japan protest over Korean assassin Ahn Jung-geun memorial in China |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-25808437 |newspaper=BBC |location= |date=January 20, 2014 |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Public opinion ==\nSurvey published in 2019 by the [[Pew Research Center]] found that 63% of South Koreans had an unfavourable view of China.<ref>{{cite news |title=People around the globe are divided in their opinions of China |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/09/30/people-around-the-globe-are-divided-in-their-opinions-of-china/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], more than half a million South Korean citizens have signed a petition lobbying the government to [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 Wuhan coronavirus outbreak|ban Chinese from entering the country]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|title=South Koreans call in petition for Chinese to be barred over virus|last=Shin|first=Hyonhee|date=28 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154836/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2010 Eocheong boat collision incident]]\n* [[2011 Gyeongryeolbi island fishing incident]]\n* [[2011 Incheon fishing incident]]\n* [[China-Japan-South Korea trilateral meeting, 2008]]\n* [[Nordpolitik]]\n* [[People's Republic of China-North Korea relations]]\n* [[Republic of China\u2013South Korea relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttp://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/04/16/0200000000AEN20170416002300315.html\nhttp://time.com/4734066/south-korea-tourism-china-thaad/\nhttps://www.inquisitr.com/4216299/president-moon-jae-in-on-thaad-and-hallyu-efforts-are-on-to-lift-chinas-ban-on-k-pop-k-drama/\nDebate on the THAAD Deployment in Korea and Policy Implications\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/krtoc.html ''Library of Congress'', A Country Study: South Korea]\n\n{{Foreign relations of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of South Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:China - South Korea Relations}}\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of China|Korea, South]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of South Korea|China, Peoples Republic]]\n[[Category:China\u2013South Korea relations| ]]\n[[Category:China\u2013Korea relations|South]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the relations between South Korea and the Taipei-based Republic of China, commonly known as Taiwan, South Korea\u2013Taiwan relations}}\n{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the People's Republic of China and South Korea}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|China\u2013South Korea|China|South Korea|envoytitle1 =[[Ambassadors of China|Ambassador]] |envoy1 = [[Qiu Guohong]]|envoytitle2 =[[Ambassadors of South Korea|Ambassador]] |envoy2 = [[Jang Ha-sung]]|mission1 = [[Embassy of People's Republic of China in South Korea|Chinese Embassy, Seoul]] |mission2 = [[Embassy of South Korea in China|Korean Embassy, Beijing]]}}\n[[File:Kr-china-embassy 201604.JPG|thumb|Chinese Embassy in [[Seoul]], South Korea.]]\n[[File:\u97e9\u56fd\u9a7b\u4e2d\u56fd\u5927\u4f7f\u9986.jpg|thumb|right|South Korean Embassy in [[Beijing]], China.]]\n\n[[Diplomatic relations]] between the [[China|People's Republic of China]] (PRC) and the Republic of Korea ([[South Korea]]) were formally established in the 1980s. Before then, the PRC recognized only the Democratic People's Republic of Korea ([[North Korea]]) while South Korea in turn recognized only the [[Republic of China]] ([[Taiwan]]). South Korea was the last Asian country to establish relations with the People's Republic of China. In recent years, China and South Korea have endeavored to boost their strategic and cooperative partnership in numerous sectors, as well as promoting high level relationship.<ref>http://www.korea.net/news.do?mode=detail&guid=47084</ref> Trade, tourism and multiculturalism, specifically, have been the most important factors of strengthening two neighbouring countries cooperative partnership.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe relations significantly deteriorated after South Korea announced its intentions to deploy [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]], a move that China strongly opposed. China imposed an unofficial boycott on South Korea in an attempt to stop them from deploying the missile system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/2083166/opinion-why-chinas-shadow-boycott-south-korea-self-defeating|title=Why China's economic jabs at South Korea are self-defeating|date=2017-04-02|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref> However, at the end of October 2017, the two countries ended the 1-year-long diplomatic dispute and have been working swiftly to get their relationship back on track since, strengthening exchanges and cooperation between each other, creating harmony of interests, and agreed to resume exchanges and cooperation in all areas. All economic and cultural bans from China towards South Korea were also lifted as a result, with political and security cooperation, businesses and cultural exchanges between the two countries getting back to healthy state.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korea, China say to mend ties after THAAD standoff|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/south-korea--china-say-to-mend-ties-after-thaad-standoff-9360436?view=DEFAULT|work=Channel NewsAsia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=China, South Korea agree to mend ties after THAAD standoff|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles/china-south-korea-agree-to-mend-ties-after-thaad-standoff-idUSKBN1D003G|work=Reuters|date=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=CNN|first1=Ben Westcott and Lauren Suk|title=China, South Korea end year-long diplomatic feud over missile system|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/31/asia/china-south-korea-thaad/index.html|work=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=AP|first1=Hyung-Jin Kim /|title=China, South Korea Ease Tensions Over U.S. Missile Defense|url=http://time.com/5003532/south-korea-china-thaad-missile-defense/|work=Time}}</ref>\n\nUpon resumption of relationship, China and South Korea have been organizing presidential and governmental visits, working together on the [[Korean Peninsula]], assisting with the development of other countries, and cooperating in numerous areas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jennings|first1=Ralph|title=South Korea Vying with China as New Benefactor for Philippines|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/south-korea-competing-with-china-in-philippine-trade/4126200.html|work=VOA|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diplomat|first1=Charlotte Gao, The|title=South Korean Foreign Minister to Visit Beijing After China Envoy's North Korea Visit|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/11/south-korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-beijing-after-china-envoys-north-korea-visit/|work=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=South Korean foreign minister to visit China to arrange presidential trip- Nikkei Asian Review|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/South-Korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-China-to-arrange-presidential-trip|work=Nikkei Asian Review|language=en|access-date=2017-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121065955/https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/South-Korean-foreign-minister-to-visit-China-to-arrange-presidential-trip|archive-date=2017-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Seoul to closely cooperate with China, Japan to tackle North Korea issue|url=https://www.upi.com/Seoul-to-closely-cooperate-with-China-Japan-to-tackle-North-Korea-issue/8351520929245/|work=UPI|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History of relations==\n{{See also|History of Sino-Korean relations|}}\n\n===Korean War===\n{{main|Korean War}}\nThe newly established [[People's Republic of China]] participated in the [[Korean War]] between 1950 and 1953, sending the [[People's Volunteer Army]] to fight alongside [[Soviet Union]] and against [[United States]] and [[United Nations]] troops in October 1950. It successfully drove the UN forces out of North Korea, but its own offensive into the South itself was repelled. The participation of the PVA strained relations between South Korea and China. The Korean War concluded in July 1953, resulting in the establishment of the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]], and the eventual withdrawal of Chinese forces from the Korean Peninsula. US troops though have remained in South Korea to this day.\n\n===Cold War===\nThroughout the [[Cold War]], there were no official relations between the PRC and ROK. The PRC maintained close relations with [[North Korea]], and South Korea maintained diplomatic relations with the Republic of China in [[Taiwan]]. This hindered trade between Seoul and Beijing, because South Korea was unable to protect its citizens and business interests in China without some form of international agreements. Beijing's economic needs involving South Korea were initially eclipsed by those of [[Moscow]].{{Clarify|reason=|date=May 2019}}<!-- what do you mean by \"eclipsed by those of Moscow\"? -->\n\n====Relations under Park and Chun (1961\u20131988)====\nPresident [[Park Chung-hee]] initiated and President [[Chun Doo-hwan]] advanced a policy of establishing relations with China and the [[Soviet Union]], and attempting to improve those with [[North Korea]]. China and the USSR had significant sway in determining the future of the [[Korean Peninsula]]. Good relations with old allies of North Korea were therefore integral to the [[Nordpolitik]] policy.\n\n[[Seoul]]'s official contact with Beijing started by the landing of a hijacked [[CAAC Flight 296]] in May 1983. China sent a delegation of thirty-three officials to Seoul to negotiate its return. This marked the beginning of a series of casual exchanges of citizens. For example, in March 1984, a South Korean tennis team visited [[Kunming]] for a [[1984 Davis Cup#Eastern Zone|Davis Cup]] match with a Chinese team. In April 1984, a thirty-four-member Chinese basketball team arrived in Seoul to participate in the Eighth Asian Junior Basketball Championships. Some Chinese officials reportedly paid quiet visits to South Korea to inspect its industries, while South Korean officials visited China to attend a range of international conferences.\n\n====Late 1980s====\nActive South Korean-Chinese individual contacts have been encouraged. Academics, journalists, and particularly families divided between South Korea and China were able to exchange visits freely in the late 1980s. Significant numbers of citizens of each country reside in the other. {{Asof|2009}}, more than 600,000 [[Chinese people in Korea|PRC citizens reside in South Korea]], of whom 70% are [[Koreans in China|ethnic Koreans]] from the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture]] in China's [[Jilin Province]] and other parts of China, while roughly 560,000 South Korean citizens lived in China.<ref name=\"BBG\">{{citation|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=ahEY6TmQOzIc&refer=home|periodical=Bloomberg L.P.|title=South Koreans Quit China as Yuan's Gain Raises Cost of Living|last=Kim|first=Kyoungwha|date=2009-01-09|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ChosunIlbo20090806\">{{citation|periodical=Chosun Ilbo|date=2009-08-06|accessdate=2009-10-18|title=More Than 1 Million Foreigners Live in Korea|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/08/06/2009080600243.html}}</ref>\n\nHowever, during this period significant barriers to strong trade and relations persisted. The absence of any protections granted by official relations had still remained. Beijing has been politically closer to Pyongyang, and relations with North Korea remained tense and distrustful.\n\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square protests]] Pyongyang publicly supported of Beijing's actions. Seoul, on the other hand, did not condone or condemn the actions in Tiananmen Square.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Post Cold War and Reform and Opening Up==\nTrade between the two countries continued to increase nonetheless, especially after the PRC's [[reform and opening up]]. Furthermore, China has attempted to mediate between North Korea and the US; between North Korea and Japan; and also initiated and promoted tripartite talks\u2014between Pyongyang, Seoul, and Washington.<ref>Zhao, Quansheng. \"China and the Korean Peace Process.\" In the Korean Peace Processand the Four Powers. Burlington: Ashgate, 2003.</ref>\n\nSouth Korea had been an ally of the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]]. But in 1992 diplomatic ties between Seoul and Taipei were nevertheless severed. On August 24, 1992 formal diplomatic relations were established between Seoul and Beijing. By 2004 China had become South Korea's leading trading partner.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Comrades in Broken Arms: Shifting Chinese Policies Toward North Korea Pg.580</ref>\n\nAfter the [[United States\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement|KORUS FTA]] (United States-Korea Free Trade Agreement) was finalized on 30 June 2007, the Chinese government immediately began seeking an FTA agreement with South Korea.<ref>\"ROK\u2019s Yonhap: Exports have been Remarkable, but can S. Korea Sustain Momentum?\" Yonhap, October 21, 2004, FBIS, KPP20041021000040.\n</ref> The [[China\u2013South Korea Free Trade Agreement|China-Republic of Korea Free Trade Agreement]] was finalized on December 20, 2015. Tariffs on 958 products including medical equipment, transformers, etc. were eliminated. On 1 January 2016, tariffs were eliminated on 5,779 products for 2 years. Also, in 10 years it is estimated that the Chinese tariffs will gradually go down and be eliminated on 5,846 products.<ref>\"China-Korea FTA.\" China FTA Network. Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China, n.d. Web.</ref> South Korea has been running a trade surplus with China, which hit a record US$32.5 billion in 2009 and total trade between the two nations surpassed US$300 billion in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.ce.cn/World/biz/201001/14/t20100114_20800769.shtml|title=S Korea posts record-high trade surplus in 2009|date=2010-01-14}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOn 29 November 2010, a [[United States diplomatic cables leak]] mentioned two unknown Chinese officials telling then Vice-Foreign Minister [[Chun Yung-woo]] that the PRC would favor a Korea reunified under the South's government, as long as it was not hostile to China.<ref>Tisdall, Simon. \"Wikileaks Cables Reveal China 'ready to Abandon North Korea'\" The Guardian, 29 Nov. 2010. Web. 7 Dec. 2010. <https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/29/wikileaks-cables-china-reunified-korea></ref>\n\n[[File:Belt and Road Initiative participant map.svg|thumb|Countries which signed cooperation documents related to the [[Belt and Road Initiative]]]]\nIt was announced on 10 January 2011 that the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (South Korea)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade (MOFAT)]] established two teams of China experts and language specialists under its department handling Chinese affairs in an effort to strengthen diplomacy.<ref>Moore, Thomas G. \"China's International Relations: The Economic Dimension.\" In The International Relations of Northeast Asia. Lanham, Md.: Rowman and Littlefield Publishers, Inc., 2004, 101.</ref> An analytical team will report on political, economic and foreign affairs developments in China, and a monitoring team consisting of seven language specialists will report on public sentiment in China. The Institute of Foreign Affairs and National Security (IFANS), a think-tank affiliated to MOFAT, also launched a centre dedicated to China affairs, which will act as a hub to collate research on China undertaken in Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.junotane.com/analytical-updates/korea-strengthens-china-analyst-team.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713125430/http://www.junotane.com/analytical-updates/korea-strengthens-china-analyst-team.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-13 |title=Korea strengthens China analyst team |date=2011-01-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe Park-Xi summit in 2013 showed promise of warming relations, but this quickly chilled after China extended their [[Air Defense Identification Zone (East China Sea)]] over South Korean territory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/is-the-china-south-korea-honeymoon-over/ |title=Is the China-South Korea Honeymoon Over? |last1=Miller |first1=J. Berkshire |date=30 November 2013 |website=thediplomat.com |publisher=The Diplomat |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> Despite this, in July 2014, Xi visited South Korea before its traditional ally North Korea, and in their talks, both leaders affirmed their support for a nuclear-free Korean peninsula and the ongoing free trade agreement negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/04/world/asia/presidents-of-china-and-south-korea-reaffirm-push-for-north-korean-denuclearization.html |title = China and South Korea Affirm Antinuclear Goals|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2014-07-03|last1 = Perlez|first1 = Jane}}</ref> Both leaders also expressed their concerns over Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]]'s reinterpretation of [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution]].\n\nIn October 2016, South Korea lodged a formal complaint with Beijing accusing Chinese fishing boats of ramming and sinking a South Korean coast guard vessel. The incident occurred on 7 October when South Korean coast guard officers were trying to stop about 40 Chinese fishing boats from suspected [[illegal fishing]] off South Korea's west coast.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/seoul-protests-to-beijing-over-sinking-of-coast-guard-vessel/2016/10/10/4654fa68-8eb8-11e6-bc00-1a9756d4111b_story.html</ref> The incidents of illegal Chinese entry continued and in 1 November 2016, South Korea ships opened fire on illegal Chinese boats. No casualties were reported.<ref>http://www.businessinsider.com/south-korea-fired-on-chinese-fishing-boats-2016-11</ref>\n\n===Deployment of THAAD in South Korea===\n\n==== Background ====\n \n[[File:Chinese tourist to South Korea.svg|thumb|right|Chinese tourists to South Korea and year-on-year rate. From March 2017, tourists plummeted in retaliation for the installation of THAAD.]]\nIn late 2016, the United States and South Korea jointly announced the deployment of the [[Terminal High-Altitude Area Defense]] (THAAD), allegedly in response to nuclear and missile threats by North Korea.<ref>Sherman, Paul Haenle and Anne. \"The Real Answer to China's THAAD Dilemma.\" The Diplomat. The Diplomat, 12 Sept. 2016.</ref> The U.S. states that the deployment of the THAAD is \u201cpurely a defensive measure\u2026 only aimed at North Korea\u201d and has no intention to threaten China's security interests. But China has continuously expressed its opposition over South Korea and U.S.\u2019s decision because of its concern that the deployment of THAAD might be a measure by the U.S. to contain China.<ref>\"Background Briefing with a Senior Administration Official on National Security Advisor Susan Rice's Visit to China July 26, 2016.\" Beijing/China. Embassy of the United States, n.d. Web.</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Reuters]]:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-missiledefence-idUSKBN1JV35W|title='No Nukes, No THAAD': South Korean town calls for missile defense...|date=2018-07-06|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-28|language=en}}</ref><blockquote>\u201cIt was China, not North Korea, that was the most uncomfortable with the idea of deploying THAAD in South Korea,\u201d said Yang Uk, a military expert at the Korea Defense and Security Forum. Beijing opposed THAAD and its powerful radar that can see deeply into Chinese territory, saying it upsets the regional security balance.</blockquote>\n\n==== Opposition from China ====\n\nStating that the THAAD will undermine China's own nuclear deterrent capability, China\u2019s Ambassador [[Qiu Guohong]] warned that the deployment of THAAD could \u201cdestroy\u201d the China\u2013South Korea ties in an instant, whereas the spokesperson of the president of South Korea warned China that deploying the THAAD is a \u201cmatter we will decide upon according to our own security and national interests.\" <ref>Tiezzi, Shannon. \"China Warns THAAD Deployment Could Destroy South Korea Ties 'in an Instant'\" The Diplomat. The Diplomat, 25 Feb. 2016.</ref>\n\nFor aims of a [[d\u00e9tente]] (a relaxation of tension), China and South Korea held a summit in [[Hangzhou]], eastern China, on Sept. 5, 2016 with each party's leaders [[Xi Jinping]] and [[Park Geun-hye|Park Geun-Hye]] to discuss the issue of THAAD. During the summit, Park reemphasized that the THAAD deployment is only to be aimed against North Korea and that there should be no reason for China's security interest to be concerned. However, Xi reiterated China's firm stance against the deployment of THAAD stating that it could \u201cintensify disputes\". Yet, the two countries still emphasized the long history of their relationship and agreed that a stable and healthy bilateral relationship will benefit both countries.<ref>Song, Sang-Ho. \"Yonhap News Agency.\" (6th LD) Park, Xi Reconfirm Differences pt. 2016.</ref>\n\n==== Effect of THAAD on South Korea's economy ====\n[[File:Hyundai Motor Sales in China.svg|thumb|right|Unit sales and year-on-year rate in China. From March 2017, unit sales plummeted in retaliation for the installation of [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]].]]\nWith South Korea's decision in 2017 to accept the deployment of [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]] in the country, although China's government shied away from formal sanctions and measures, it has urged its citizens through official media to express their displeasure and ill will at South Korea over the move.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-china-blog-39254254</ref> Chinese citizens were allowed to gather to protest. The news media has reported of citizen boycotts of South Korean products like [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]] cars, of South Korean goods being removed from supermarket shelves, and tourists and travel companies canceling trips to South Korea.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\" />\n\nSouth Korean conglomerate [[Lotte (conglomerate)|Lotte Group]] became a particular focus. Lotte had agreed to an exchange of land, a golf course in [[Seongju County|Seongju]], with the South Korean government that will be used for the THAAD deployment. In addition to a consumer boycott of Lotte stores in China, municipal authorities suddenly discovered that Lotte stores and factories to be in contravention of [[fire safety]] regulations and other local ordinances which has resulted in the closure of 75 out of 99 Lotte supermarkets.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen|first1=Jethro|last2=Han |first2=Sol |date=7 March 2017|title=One company is bearing the brunt of China's anger over U.S. missile system |url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/03/07/news/china-lotte-thaad-south-korea-tensions/ | work=[[CNN Money]] |location= |access-date=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Javier |last2=Guo |first2=Owen |last3=McMorrow |first3=Ryan  |date=9 March 2017 \n|title=South Korean Stores Feel China's Wrath as U.S. Missile System Is Deployed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/world/asia/china-lotte-thaad-south-korea.html?_r=0 | work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |access-date=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nMarch sales of Hyundai and its sister brand [[Kia Motors]] in China plunged 52 per cent from a year earlier to 72,000 vehicles, the lowest level since 2014.<ref name=\"SCMP20170405\">{{cite web |title=South Korea's Hyundai, Kia sales halve in China amid diplomatic spat over THAAD |date=5 April 2017 |publisher=South China Morning Post |url=http://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2085118/south-koreas-hyundai-kia-sales-halve-china-amid-diplomatic-spat}}</ref> Chinese tourism also plummeted 39.4% (compared to March 2016) in March.<ref>{{cite web |title=3\uc6d4 \uc911\uad6d\uc778 \uad00\uad11\uac1d 39% \uc904\uc5b4\u2026 '\uc0ac\ub4dc \ubcf4\ubcf5' \uc601\ud5a5 |trans-title=Chinese tourists decrease by 39% in March ... Impact of 'THAAD Revenge' |publisher=Yonhapnews |date=April 5, 2017 \n|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2017/04/05/0200000000AKR20170405120251030.HTML}}</ref> As a result, China has become a more hated country in South Korea than even Japan, according to an opinion poll conducted by the [[Asan Institute for Policy Studies]] in March 2017.<ref>Alex Linder(2017-03-22):[http://shanghaiist.com/2017/03/22/south_koreans_like_japan_over_china.php South Koreans now hate China even more than Japan, new opinion polls says], ''[[Shanghaiist]]''</ref>\n\nAs a result, South Korea's distribution industry suffered. Chinese consumers were no longer attracted to Korean products and Chinese retailers boycotted Korean products. As a result of decreased Chinese consumption, South Korean department stores, duty-free, restaurants, and the automobile industry were severely affected. However, Korean conglomerates had to survive since China is the largest market in the world.\n\nHyundai had to stop the operation of Chinese factories and the economic losses were significant. The vicious cycle has been repeated as the decline of sales volume caused production suspension. Chinese automobile component manufacturing companies suspended distribution to Hyundai automobile factories that are located in China and it negatively affected the management of Hyundai automobile. THAAD had a tremendous impact on Korean economy in various business sectors and tarnished the brand value of Korean companies because of political reasons.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==== Culture ====\nKorean culture, singers, actors and dancers are popular with Chinese youth because of the development of the internet and export of Korean cultural content. After the THAAD dispute took place, a \"Korea limitation order\" ({{zh|s=\u9650\u97e9\u4ee4}}) was placed upon [[Hallyu]]. In China, Hallyu cultural events were canceled, Korean actors had to quit from their works and limited Korean media could be exported to China. The ban was lifted soon after, and relations cooled.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Historical controversies==\nThe Chinese historical claims surrounding [[Goguryeo]] and its related kingdoms created some tension between Korea and the PRC.<ref>[http://www.ou.edu/uschina/gries/articles/texts/Gries2005KoguryoEAIQ.pdf 02Gries.pmd<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The PRC government has recently begun the [[Northeast Project]], a controversial Chinese government research project claiming [[Goguryeo]] and other various Korean kingdoms, including [[Gojoseon]], [[Buyeo kingdom|Buyeo]] and [[Balhae]], to be Chinese tributary states. This sparked a massive uproar in South Korea when the project was widely publicized in 2004.<ref name=\"news.naver.com\">Donga Monthly. http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=037&aid=0000006961</ref>\n\n== Joint stance on Japan ==\n{{Main|History of Sino-Japanese relations|People's Republic of China\u2013Japan relations|History of Japan\u2013Korea relations|Japan\u2013South Korea relations|Japan\u2013Korea disputes}}\nDue to the [[Empire of Japan]] and atrocities committed by the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] on both Koreans and Chinese, from women who supplied sex during WWII(known as [[comfort women]]) and the [[Japanese colonization of Korea]] to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] and [[Unit 731]], South Korea and China are unified in their stance against Japan and insistence on greater reparations for Japan wartime atrocities.\n\n=== 1910-1945 provisional ROK government ===\n{{Main|Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea}}\nWhen the Korean peninsula was colonized by Imperial Japan, [[Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea|the provisional government of the ROK]] in exile in Shanghai received the support of China.\n\n=== Japanese war crimes ===\nBoth the governments of China and South Korea take a firm stand on issues in relation to [[Japanese war crimes]]. Korea had been under [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]] after the collapse of the [[Joseon Dynasty]] in 1910. During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], [[Japan]] invaded and occupied eastern China.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] perpetrated many war crimes against both Chinese and Koreans. This has caused both to oppose the Japanese government's stand on war crimes committed during the war. Issues where both the Chinese and South Korean governments stand together include the controversial visits of Japanese politicians to the [[Yasukuni Shrine]], the [[Japanese history textbook controversies]], and [[comfort women]].\n\n=== An Jung-geun ===\nIn 2014, a memorial dedicated to Korean assassin [[An Jung-geun]] was opened in the Chinese city of [[Harbin]], where he assassinated Japanese Prime Minister [[It\u014d Hirobumi]] in 1909. The Japanese government protested the move, referring to An as a \"terrorist\".<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Japan protest over Korean assassin Ahn Jung-geun memorial in China |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-25808437 |newspaper=BBC |location= |date=January 20, 2014 |access-date=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Public opinion ==\nSurvey published in 2019 by the [[Pew Research Center]] found that 63% of South Koreans had an unfavourable view of China.<ref>{{cite news |title=People around the globe are divided in their opinions of China |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/09/30/people-around-the-globe-are-divided-in-their-opinions-of-china/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nMore than half a million South Korean citizens have signed a petition lobbying the government to [[Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 Wuhan coronavirus outbreak|ban Chinese from entering the country]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|title=South Koreans call in petition for Chinese to be barred over virus|last=Shin|first=Hyonhee|date=28 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154836/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2010 Eocheong boat collision incident]]\n* [[2011 Gyeongryeolbi island fishing incident]]\n* [[2011 Incheon fishing incident]]\n* [[China-Japan-South Korea trilateral meeting, 2008]]\n* [[Nordpolitik]]\n* [[People's Republic of China-North Korea relations]]\n* [[Republic of China\u2013South Korea relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttp://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/04/16/0200000000AEN20170416002300315.html\nhttp://time.com/4734066/south-korea-tourism-china-thaad/\nhttps://www.inquisitr.com/4216299/president-moon-jae-in-on-thaad-and-hallyu-efforts-are-on-to-lift-chinas-ban-on-k-pop-k-drama/\nDebate on the THAAD Deployment in Korea and Policy Implications\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/krtoc.html ''Library of Congress'', A Country Study: South Korea]\n\n{{Foreign relations of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of South Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:China - South Korea Relations}}\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of China|Korea, South]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of South Korea|China, Peoples Republic]]\n[[Category:China\u2013South Korea relations| ]]\n[[Category:China\u2013Korea relations|South]]\n", "name_user": "ROBLOXGamingDavid", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic opinion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China%E2%80%93South_Korea_relations"}
{"title_page": "Museum of Army Chaplaincy", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=November 2019}}\nThe '''Museum of Army Chaplaincy''' is a museum  which tells the story of [[British Army]] [[military chaplain|chaplaincy]] from earliest times to the present day, with the help of archive material and historical relics from several centuries.  The museum was originally housed in [[Bagshot Park]], Surrey, but in 2001 was rehoused in a converted stable block at [[Amport House]] in Hampshire which was the home of the [[RAChD|Royal Army Chaplains' Department]] within the Tri-Service Armed Forces Chaplaincy Centre.\n\nThe museum holds a unique collection dedicated to the work of Army Chaplains throughout history in peacetime, under fire, and in captivity. The museum archives also hold material relating to the department and its history, including information on the four chaplains who have been awarded the [[Victoria Cross]].\n\nThe museum will relocate from Amport House to the [[Defence Academy of the United Kingdom|Defence Academy]] site at [[Shrivenham]], near Swindon, in 2020. To enable preparation for the move, the museum has been closed to visitors since 1 November 2019.  \n\nThe curator of the museum is David Blake, formerly of the [[Cheshire Military Museum]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[U.S. Army Chaplain Museum]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{official}}\n*[https://twitter.com/ArmyChaplainMus Official Twitter]\n\n{{coord|51.1955|-1.5767|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Museum of Army Chaplaincy}}\n[[Category:Museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Army museums in England]]\n[[Category:Religious museums in England|Army]]\n[[Category:Military chaplains| Royal Army Chaplains' Department M]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Chaplains' Department]]\n\n{{England-org-stub}}\n{{UK-museum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=November 2019}}\nThe '''Museum of Army Chaplaincy''' is a museum  which tells the story of [[British Army]] [[military chaplain|chaplaincy]] from earliest times to the present day, with the help of archive material and historical relics from several centuries.  The museum was originally housed in [[Bagshot Park]], Surrey, but in 2001 was rehoused at [[Amport House]] in Hampshire which was the home of the [[RAChD|Royal Army Chaplains' Department]] within the Tri-Service Armed Forces Chaplaincy Centre.\n\nHoused in a converted stable block, the museum holds a unique collection dedicated to the work of Army Chaplains throughout history in peacetime, under fire, and in captivity. The museum archives also hold material relating to the department and its history, including information on the four chaplains who have been awarded the [[Victoria Cross]].\n\nThe museum will relocate from Amport House to the [[Defence Academy of the United Kingdom|Defence Academy]] site at [[Shrivenham]], near Swindon, in 2020. To enable preparation for the move, the museum has not been open to visitors after 1 November 2019.  \n\nThe curator of the museum is David Blake, formerly of the [[Cheshire Military Museum]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[U.S. Army Chaplain Museum]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{official}}\n*[https://twitter.com/ArmyChaplainMus Official Twitter]\n\n{{coord|51.1955|-1.5767|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Museum of Army Chaplaincy}}\n[[Category:Museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Army museums in England]]\n[[Category:Religious museums in England|Army]]\n[[Category:Military chaplains| Royal Army Chaplains' Department M]]\n[[Category:Royal Army Chaplains' Department]]\n\n{{England-org-stub}}\n{{UK-museum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wire723", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Minor copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Museum_of_Army_Chaplaincy"}
{"title_page": "Paul Martin (illustrator)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on over two dozen covers of ''[[Collier's]]'' and ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' during the 1920s. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York]] area from 1909 to 1931. Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as more commercially, than creatively inspired. Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photograph), 26 (description). Scroll far downward. It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]] ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689, 691. Another source with photo/desc.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click icon>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature.</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no in-print proof. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Lithographic, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref><ref name=\"reading\">''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The cover model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts''. Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966).<ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref> They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debuted 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He previously worked as a brokerage clerk.</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #232.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number, in parenthesis.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on over two dozen covers of ''[[Collier's]]'' and ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' during the 1920s. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York area]] from 1909 to 1931. Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as more commercially, than creatively inspired. Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photograph), 26 (description). Scroll far downward. It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]] ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689, 691. Another source with photo/desc.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click icon>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature.</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no in-print proof. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Lithographic, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref><ref name=\"reading\">''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The cover model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts''. Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966).<ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref> They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debuted 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He previously worked as a brokerage clerk.</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #232.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number, in parenthesis.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "JimPercy", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed word position", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Martin_(illustrator)"}
{"title_page": "Butrint Imeri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}} \n{{Short description|Kosovo singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Butrint Imeri\n| image            =  \n| caption          =  \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       =  \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1996|07|03}}\n| birth_place      = [[L\u00f6rrach]], Germany\n| origin           =  \n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|Pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}} \n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = 96 Management\n| associated_acts  =  \n}}\n \n'''Butrint Imeri''' ({{IPA-sq|bu\u02c8t\u027eint i\u02c8m\u025b\u027ei}}; born 3 July 1996) is a [[Kosovo]]- singer and songwriter.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web |title=Butrint Imeri\u2013Biografia |url=https://www.teksteshqip.com/butrint |website=teksteshqip.com |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian }}</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nButrint Imeri was born on 3 July 1996 into a Kosovo family in the city of [[L\u00f6rrach]], Germany. He commenced his music career in 2015 and debuted with the singles, \"Ki me lyp\", \"Merre zemr\u00ebn tem\" and \"Eja Eja\", with whom he received significant recognition in the [[Kosovo language|Kosovo-speaking]] world.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lansohet klipi i Butrintit me Real dhe Blunt |url=https://telegrafi.com/lansohet-klipi-i-butrintit-me-real-dhe-blunt-video/ |website=telegrafi.com |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=20 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ylli i ri Butrint Imeri thot\u00eb \u201cMerre Zemr\u00ebn tem\u201d |url=https://telegrafi.com/ylli-i-ri-butrint-imeri-thote-merre-zemren-tem-video/ |website=telegrafi.com |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=10 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Butrint Imeri me nj\u00eb k\u00ebng\u00eb t\u00eb p\u00eblqyeshme |url=https://telegrafi.com/butrint-imeri-nje-kenge-te-pelqyeshme-video/ |website=telegrafi.com |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=12 April 2016}}</ref> He later released four additional singles including \"E jona\" and \"Delicious\", the latter in collaboration with Greek-Albanian singer [[Eleni Foureira]] which peaked at number five in [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vie \u2018E Jona\u2019 nga Butrint Imeri! |url=https://priveshow.tv/vie-e-jona-nga-butrinti/ |website=[[Klan Kosova|prive.tv]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=3 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Butrint publikon duetin me Eleni Foureira |url=https://www.botasot.info/mediale-vip-showbiz/552898/butrint-publikon-duetin-me-eleni-foureira-video/ |website=[[Bota Sot|botasot.info]] |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\nImeri's musical work is often defined as [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Pop music|Pop]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Butrint Imeri\u2013Bio |url=http://topawards.top-channel.tv/index.php/artist/butrint-imeri/ |website=topawards.top-channel.tv |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=Albanian}}</ref><ref name=\"Biography\"/> He has cited [[Justin Timberlake]] as his major musical influence and stated that he is a fan of [[Elvana Gjata]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cil\u00ebn k\u00ebng\u00ebtare shqiptare e ka t\u00eb preferuar Butrinti |url=https://prive.al/cilen-kengetare-shqiptare-e-ka-te-preferuar-butrinti/ |website=prive.al |accessdate=10 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=20 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Butrint Imeri e thot\u00eb hapur: Un\u00eb dhe Elvana Gjata do ishim \u00e7ifti perfekt |url=https://www.dailyxing.com/news/32143/butrint-imeri-says-it-openly-elvana-gjata-and-i-would-be-the-perfect-couple |website=dailyxing.com |accessdate=10 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n==== As lead artist ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope